# jemdoc: menu{MENU}{grad_courses.html}, nofooter  
= Grad Courses I Took

First, [pdf/academic_records.pdf here] is an unfficial copy my MS transcript. Below are the list of courses I took, chronologically ordered. Taking all courses that are somehow related to my research, I count myself lucky:

\n

- *[http://www2.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/courses/cmpe489/fall2011/ Cognitive Science]*, by /[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~salah/ Albert Ali Salah]/: An introductory to cognitive science. In each week, we covered a different topic including *brain*, *sensation&cognition*, *language*, *attention*, *learning* and *memory*.

- *[https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/9787379/cmpe58k/index.html Bayesian Statistics & Machine Learning]*, by /[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~cemgil/ Ali Taylan Cemgil]/: The main focus in this course was *graphical models*, in particular inference and parameter learning in *Hidden Markov Model* and *Kalman Filter*. We also had a poster session at the end of the semester, where I showed an application of Mixed Memory Markov Models. So, *[pdf/547-poster.pdf here]* the outcome of this course, or my first poster.

- *[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~ethem/i2ml2e/ Pattern Recognition]*, by /[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~ethem/ Ethem Alpaydın]/: The course was about traditional machine learning. We covered first 9 chapters of Ethem Hoca's [https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/introduction-machine-learning Introduction to Machine Learning] book: parametric/semiparametric/nonparametric methods for *classification*, *regression* and *clustering*, *PCA*, *LDA*, *decision trees*, and *HMM*'s. We also worked on a term project, in which I compared three Markov models, namely, Hidden Markov Model, Mixed Memory Markov Model and Factorial Markov Model. Resulting report is *[pdf/544-paper.pdf here]*.

- *[http://www.ie.boun.edu.tr/?q=courses/ie-515-graphs-and-network-flows Graphs & Network Flows]*, by /[http://www.ie.boun.edu.tr/?q=faculty/z-caner-ta%C5%9Fk%C4%B1n Caner Taşkın]/: *Shortest path*, *max-flow&min-cut*, *min cost flow/circulation problems* and problems with side constraints were the main subjects. I compared execution times of four different algorithms for maximum flow problem in various types of networks in my term project and *[pdf/515-paper.pdf here]* is the report.

- *[https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/9787379/cmpe58n/index.html Monte Carlo Methods]*, by /[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~cemgil/ Ali Taylan Cemgil]/: A follow-up course to Bayesian Statistics. We investigated *random number generation*, *rejection sampling*, *importance sampling*, discrete space *Markov chains*, *Metropolis-Hastings algorithm*, *Gibbs sampler* and *sequential Monte Carlo*. That was I guess my favorite course among all in this list. As a term project, I built Mixed Memory Hidden Markov Model for time series analysis, which is briefly described in [projects.html projects] sections, and implemented parameter learning via Gibbs sampler, Metropolis algorithm and particle filter. *[pdf/548-poster.pdf Here]* is the my poster.

- *[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~ethem/i2ml2e/ Artificial Neural Networks]*, by /[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~ethem/ Ethem Alpaydın]/: The rest of Ethem Hoca's [https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/introduction-machine-learning Introduction to Machine Learning] book is covered in this course. In particular, we studied *multilayer perceptrons*, *recurrent & convolutional neural networks*, *kernel machines & support vector machines*, *mixture of experts* and *reinforcement learning*. My term project was about clustering and prediction in time series. I implemented self organized maps and hierarchical clustering for the first part and 4 types of neural networks for the second part: /Tapped-delay multilayer perceptron/, /Elman RNN/, /Full lag Elman RNN/ and /Tapped-delay Jordan RNN/. *[pdf/545-poster.pdf Here]* is my report.

- *[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/tr/courses/cmpe540 Principles of Artificial Intelligence]*, by /[http://www.cmpe.boun.edu.tr/~salah/ Albert Ali Salah]/: *Intelligent & problem solving agents*, *problem types and search methods*, *heuristics*, *genetic algorithms*, *constraint satisfaction problems* and *games* were the main topics of the course. We designed agents that plays [https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/148228/splendor splendor] in Prolog. My term paper was about *Bayesian approaches in human cognition* and *[pdf/540-term.pdf here]* is the report. Also, *[pdf/480-report.pdf see]* my term project report for Introduction to AI course, titled as *Philosophy of Artificial Intelligence*.

- *[http://www.ie.boun.edu.tr/sites/default/files/IE505_Fall15_syllabus.pdf Stochastic Processes & Applications]*, by /[http://www.ie.boun.edu.tr/?q=faculty/aybek-korugan Aybek Korugan]/: I took this course from [www.ie.boun.edu.tr Industrial Engineering] department. The requirements were different than courses in our department, so we took 3 exams and no term project. We covered *branching processes*, *random walks*, *Markov chains* and *Poisson processes* in this course.
